<h2 id="what-is-shopify">🛒 What Is Shopify?</h2>

Shopify is a hosted ecommerce platform that handles storefront creation, payment processing, inventory management, and fulfillment coordination. Unlike self-hosted alternatives like WooCommerce or Magento, Shopify manages servers, security patches, and platform updates. You focus on selling; they handle infrastructure.

The platform serves everyone from side-hustle sellers to enterprise brands processing millions monthly. For operators, the relevant tiers are Shopify (formerly "Basic"), Advanced, and Shopify Plus. Each tier unlocks different multi-location capabilities, staff accounts, and API limits that matter at scale.

In 2026, Shopify expanded significantly into B2B wholesale, subscription commerce, and physical retail through enhanced POS features. The platform now processes over $250 billion in annual GMV across 4.5 million merchants. That scale means the ecosystem of apps, themes, and integrations is unmatched—but it also means you're competing for support resources with millions of other stores.

<h2 id="our-experience">📊 Our Experience Managing Ecommerce at Scale</h2>

Our team has collectively operated ecommerce across thousands of business locations. We've migrated stores from Magento, BigCommerce, and custom builds to Shopify. We've also migrated away from Shopify when it wasn't the right fit. This isn't theoretical—we've processed real transactions, handled real inventory discrepancies, and dealt with real customer service escalations across every major platform.

Here's what that experience taught us about Shopify specifically:

<strong>The 10-location inflection point is real.</strong> Shopify handles 1-9 locations smoothly on Advanced plans. At 10+ locations, you need Plus, and the operational complexity requires dedicated staff or agency support. The platform doesn't break—your processes do. Inventory sync delays that were invisible at 3 locations create visible customer complaints at 15.

<strong>App dependency creates hidden costs.</strong> Shopify's core platform intentionally stays lean. Advanced features—loyalty programs, subscription management, sophisticated shipping rules—require third-party apps. A single storefront might add $200-400/month in apps. Multiply that across locations, and you're looking at $2,000-4,000/month in app costs alone before Shopify's platform fees.

<strong>Support quality varies dramatically by tier.</strong> Standard Shopify support handles basic questions competently. But when inventory sync fails between your POS and online store at 6 PM on Black Friday, you need someone who can actually access your account backend. That level of support requires Plus or a Shopify Partner relationship. We've documented response time differences of 4 hours (Plus) versus 48 hours (Advanced) for equivalent severity issues.

For operators evaluating platform options, we've also covered the broader ecommerce landscape in our <a href="/guides/choosing-ecommerce-platform-multi-location">guide to choosing an ecommerce platform for multi-location businesses</a>.

<h2 id="key-features">⚙️ Key Features for Multi-Location Operators</h2>

<h3>Unified Inventory Management</h3>

Shopify's 2026 inventory system tracks stock across unlimited locations with real-time sync. Each location maintains independent stock counts, but a unified dashboard shows aggregate availability. The system automatically routes orders to the nearest fulfillment location based on proximity, stock levels, and custom rules you define.

The standout addition this year is predictive restock alerts. The AI analyzes sales velocity, seasonality, and lead times to recommend reorder points. Across our test portfolio, this reduced stockouts by 34% compared to manual threshold management. However, the predictions require 90+ days of sales history per SKU—new products still need manual oversight.

<div class="callout-blue">
<strong>Operator Tip:</strong> Configure location-specific safety stock levels rather than relying on Shopify's defaults. High-velocity locations need larger buffers; slow-moving showroom inventory can run leaner. This reduced our carrying costs by 18% without increasing stockout rates.
</div>

<h3>Shopify POS Pro</h3>

The point-of-sale system is where Shopify genuinely outperforms competitors for omnichannel operators. POS Pro ($89/month per location) syncs inventory, customer data, and sales reporting between physical and online channels in near real-time. Staff can fulfill online orders from retail inventory, process returns for online purchases in-store, and access complete customer purchase history regardless of channel.

Hardware options have expanded to include self-checkout kiosks and mobile tap-to-pay through iPhone and Android devices. For pop-up retail or markets, the mobile option eliminates dedicated hardware costs entirely.

<h3>Shopify Markets</h3>

International selling improved significantly in 2026. Shopify Markets handles currency conversion, international payment methods, duties and import taxes calculation, and localized checkout experiences. You can configure market-specific pricing, product availability, and shipping options without maintaining separate storefronts.

For operators expanding internationally, this consolidation matters. Managing separate stores per country creates inventory silos, reporting fragmentation, and multiplication of app subscriptions. Shopify Markets keeps everything unified while still allowing localization.

<h3>Flow Automation</h3>

Shopify Flow—previously Plus-only—now comes standard on Advanced plans. The visual workflow builder handles conditional automation: tag customers based on behavior, adjust inventory levels based on rules, send internal notifications for specific order conditions, and route orders to specific fulfillment processes.

Our team uses Flow extensively for fraud prevention, high-value order flagging, and inventory alerts. One workflow alone—automatically canceling orders from flagged addresses—prevented $12,000 in chargebacks last year across our portfolio.

<h3>B2B and Wholesale</h3>

The B2B channel features matured considerably. You can now run wholesale and DTC from a single store with customer-specific pricing, net payment terms, draft orders for sales reps, and volume-based discounts. Previously, this required separate wholesale storefronts or apps like Wholesale Club.

<div class="callout-orange">
<strong>Warning:</strong> B2B features require Shopify Plus for full functionality. The Advanced plan offers limited B2B tools, but net payment terms, company accounts, and vaulted payment methods need Plus. If wholesale represents significant revenue, factor Plus pricing into your cost calculations.
</div>

