<h2 id="who-its-for">👥 Who Shopify Is (and Isn't) For</h2>

<strong>Ideal for:</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Operators running 1-50 physical retail locations with ecommerce integration</li>
  <li>DTC brands scaling from startup to $10M+ annually</li>
  <li>Multi-brand portfolios wanting unified backend management</li>
  <li>Teams without dedicated development resources needing self-service capabilities</li>
  <li>Businesses requiring robust POS with true omnichannel inventory</li>
</ul>

<strong>Consider alternatives if:</strong>
<ul>
  <li>You need deep customization of checkout flows (Shopify Plus helps but still has limits)</li>
  <li>Your margins can't absorb transaction fees and you have payment processing relationships to leverage</li>
  <li>You're running a B2B-only operation with complex quoting and approval workflows</li>
  <li>You require on-premise hosting for compliance or data sovereignty reasons</li>
  <li>Your product catalog exceeds 100,000 SKUs with complex variant structures</li>
</ul>

<div class="callout-blue">
<strong>Operator Tip:</strong> If you're currently on WooCommerce or Magento and considering migration, audit your current app/extension costs first. Shopify's app ecosystem often provides equivalent functionality, but pricing structures differ. We've seen migrations where app costs increased 40%—and others where they decreased 60%. Run the actual numbers.
</div>

