<h2 id="final-verdict">🏆 Final Verdict</h2>

Shopify in 2026 remains the default recommendation for most ecommerce operators. The platform's reliability, ecosystem depth, and continued feature investment justify that position. Competitors have closed gaps in specific areas—BigCommerce on native B2B features, Wix on ease of use for simple stores—but none match Shopify's combination of power and accessibility.

The cost reality check matters though. Budget $200-500/month total at startup, but expect $1,500-3,000/month as you scale past 5 locations with proper app infrastructure. At 10+ locations, you're looking at $3,000-6,000/month all-in. These costs are competitive with alternatives when you factor in development resources those alternatives require.

For our team's portfolios, Shopify handles 80% of use cases optimally. The remaining 20%—highly custom B2B, massive catalogs, specific compliance requirements—warrant evaluating alternatives. But for the typical multi-location operator selling physical or digital goods across online and in-store channels, Shopify's operational efficiency gains outweigh its costs.

The platform won't solve operational problems—no software does. But it removes infrastructure friction so you can focus on the operational problems that actually drive revenue.

